thoritarian and democratic hegemonies -- tFrom Glory to Menace II Society: African American Subalternity and the Ungovernability of the Democratic Impulse under Super- Capitalist Orders -- tTwenty Preliminary Propositions for a Critical History of International Statecraft in Haiti -- tDeath in the Andes: Ungovernability and the Birth of Tragedy in Peru -- tOutside In and Inside Out: Visualizing Society in Bolivia -- tV. citizenship: resistance, transgression, disobedience -- tThe Teaching Machine for the Wild Citizen -- tApprenticeship as Citizenship and Governability -- tThe Architectural Relationship between Gender, Race, and the Bolivian State -- tGender, Citizenship, and Social Protest: The New Social Movements in Argentina -- tWho's the Indian in Aztlán? Re-Writing Mestizaje, Indianism, and Chicanismo from the Lacandón -- tColoniality of Power and Subalternity -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSharing a postrevolutionary sympathy with the struggles of the poor, the contributors to this first comprehensive collection of writing on subalternity in Latin America work to actively link politics, culture, and literature. Emerging from a decade of work and debates generated by a collective known as the Latin American Studies Group, the volume privileges the category of the subaltern over that of class, as contributors focus on the possibilities of investigating history from below.In addition to an overview by Ranajit Guha, essay topics include nineteenth-century hygiene in Latin American countries, Rigoberta Menchú after the Nobel, commentaries on Haitian and Argentinian issues, the relationship between gender and race in Bolivia, and ungovernability and tragedy in Peru. Providing a radical critique of elite culture and of liberal, bourgeois, and modern epistemologies and projects, the essays included here prove that Latin American Subaltern Studies is much more than the mere translation of subaltern studies from South Asia to Latin America.Contributors. Marcelo Bergman, John Beverley, Robert Carr, Sara Castro-Klarén, Michael Clark, Beatriz González Stephan, Ranajit Guha, María Milagros López , Walter Mignolo, Alberto Moreiras, Abdul-Karim Mustapha, José Rabasa, Ileana Rodríguez, Josefina Saldaña-Portillo, Javier Sanjinés, C. Patricia Seed, Doris Sommer, Marcia Stephenson, Mónica Szurmuk, Gareth Williams, Marc Zimmerman  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aMarginality, SocialzLatin America. 0aMinoritieszLatin America. 0aPoorzLatin America. 7aHISTORY / Latin America / General.2bisacsh1 aMustapha, Abdul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoreiras, Alberto, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStephan, Beatriz, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSommer, Doris, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWilliams, Gareth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGuha, Ranajit1 aRodríguez, Ileana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSanjinés, Javier, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeverley, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPortillo, Josefina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRabasa, José, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLópez, María Milagros, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aZimmerman, Marc, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBergman, Marcelo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStephenson, Marcia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/re